The Trojan horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be allocated.
Conditions will have to be set.
The Greek government will make usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be insurmountable, but there will be problems to come.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was to have allowed Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was already clear, however, that the country was not ready.
Its budget policy was already uncontrolled when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, in that such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if not, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy do a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face strong budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek help.
It all raises one question: was the true mistake not creating the euro in the first place?
In as much as I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you would be justified in asking me: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not a mistake, but it could become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway down the road to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could make this one seem like a walk in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency funding mechanism.
Today, EU members can only provide aid to Greece by exceeding the regulation that prevents them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide aid, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it should be modified.
Furthermore, aid should not only be granted under certain conditions, but should also be accompanied by temporary national budget control by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
History shows us that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries that will be subject to such measures will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Notice that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the former Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed its budget over to an expert appointed specifically by the administration of President Barack Obama?
Actually, they wouldn't be too bothered by that.
The expert wouldn't be from California, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the California state as well as the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from whom the orders of this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do things like this because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe truly wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic links, but also closer political ties.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for their actions.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of bailout because they know exactly who will foot the bill.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany has its part of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not accountable for its actions, but it has now adopted a monetary policy that is too excessive, thus critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
Germany's large current surpluses only exacerbate their situation further.
Furthermore, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
It should return the favor.
It should encourage the creation of an emergency lending facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
It should provide more budgetary support.
Isn't it best placed to pressure for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe towards more advanced political integration.
We can only hope for that.
